Description: Join us at 12pm ET during the Women in STEM Career Fair for a featured Fireside Chat with Maya Ajmera, President and CEO of Society for Science and Publisher of its award-winning magazine, Science News. Founded in 1921, the Society works to promote the understanding and appreciation of science and the vital role it plays in human advancement and is best known for its world-class science competitions, including the Regeneron Science Talent Search, Regeneron International Science and Engineering Fair, and Broadcom MASTERS.

Maya is the recipient of the 2020 National Science Board Public Service Award, recognized for her tremendous contribution to increasing the public’s understanding of science and engineering. Maya is also a recipient of the Henry Crown Fellowship at the Aspen Institute, the Echoing Green Fellowship, the William C. Friday Fellowship for Human Relations, and the Rotary International Graduate Fellowship.

Then, at 3pm ET join us for a panel discussion where we will be breaking Beyond the Glass Ceiling. Panelists from Infosys Foundation USA, Trinity Life Sciences, Holland & Hart LLP and Instrumental will be in attendance. We will be discussing how to navigate the interview process, negotiating offers and Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion.

Our panelists include:
Katherine Maloney, Executive Director at Infosys Foundation USA
Alessa Moscoco, Associate Director DEI at Trinity Life Sciences
Leah Villarreal, Patent Agent at Holland & Hart LLP
Anna-Katrina Shedletsky, CEO and Founder of Instrumental

The match event will run similar to a career fair, just virtually. From your computer, utilizing the platform Brazen, you will be able to go booth-to-booth and meet with the employers. While this is not an interview (in the sense of whether or not you get to participate in Sprinternship), this does give you and the employers the opportunity to meet each other beforehand and see if you will be a good fit together. first impression - put context- very important - your work don't speak for itself- always ask who, where, what, why, how, what's the relation to this and that- build trust- put the overview, challenge, goal & make it clear - what value it will bring to your client- consistency- 3-5 solid examples/projects or put experiments for unfinished projects- double check spelling and grammar- use/put captions- have empathy, don't assume that they already know - share unique POV- be clear in your specialization

Hello once again, Bean Morris gardeners!  As promised I am sending you a calendar invite and Zoom meeting instructions for your garden meeting, which is coming up at 11 am this coming Monday, April 20.


Be aware that this meeting is only going to last 40 minutes, which is the length of time that we can use Zoom for free to meet!  At the meeting, we hope to discuss and clarify the roles that you have assigned each other for the opening of the garden, whenever the pandemic-related restrictions are lifted.


At this meeting, we are also going to welcome my GreenThumb colleague Babbie Dunnington, who will provide us advice on what plants we have available to give you to plant.  Attached is a sheet that she has created of the many plants that are available.


Attached also is a quick and handy guide for gardeners about the different tools you can use to hold virtual meetings during this time--as I mentioned in my previous blast to you this morning, you can join our informational webinar about holding virtual meetings at 12 noon today--in just a few minutes!  Here is the link for the webinar:  https://zoom.us/j/656486344?pwd=TExibk5lZVNJZzlpcXIzWTU3ZkkxZz09, and here is the link for the slide deck of informational materials for today's webinar: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1B-G2Ua7xGjRUoZxjhpDhblQBMi-fzc1ccyFHMVxD6NE/edit#slide=id.p4.


Below is the information you need to join the garden meeting on April 20.  When you click on the Zoom link, you should be able to open Zoom either in your browser or download it to open as a separate application on your computer.  Do this whenever you are ready to join a Zoom meeting.


Please let me know anytime if you have questions or issues?  All the best --Amber

Subject: RE: Morris Garden - Next Steps for 2020!



Dear Friends at Morris Garden:


Thanks so much to all of you who are a part of the garden, and all of you who were able to be a part of the meeting yesterday.  I'm going to try to summarize the conversation below.


New garden name: The Bean Morris Garden, in honor of garden leader Carrie's son, nicknamed Bean, who left this world in December.  This new name seems to me to be a great first decision for the group to make.  Unless there are any objections from the group, garden will proceed with this new name.


Scheduling of garden clean-up event and the opening event to come after it: Group decided that it cannot make a plan to convene in the garden until the social-distancing restrictions in NYC have ended.  Once we have a sense of when members can come together in the garden, a date will be set for the opening event and a volunteer clean-up day to come first.  We **hope** that the garden could open around the beginning of June.


Opening Event: Several Bean Morris members attended our Event Planning Workshop last month and are ready to plan a great event to open the garden, whenever it opens.  Attached is a handout from the workshop.  Feel free to form a sub-committee among yourselves and discuss ideas, assign roles, responsibilities, purchases, etc. for the opening event--this is a great time to get as much planning as possible done before the event is scheduled.


Next meeting: We scheduled our next meeting for Monday, April 20, at 11 am, and we would like to use the application Zoom to make this next meeting a video conference, for those who are able to use Zoom.  We have been using Zoom for our office meetings, it's free and easy, and in this time of isolation it has been pretty useful!  You can download the app on your phone or your computer, you can get it ahead of time or at the linkhere<https://zoom.us/download>, and I will send you a link to click on at the time of the meeting.  Zoom also has an audio-only function, so that you can use any telephone to call in and join the meeting by voice, and I will send you the number for that as well.  I believe that Ms. Grace offered to be secretary for the group, so she will take minutes for the meeting and share with the group afterwards--Ms. Grace, just let me know if that plan changes?


Special guest appearance: At that next meeting, we have invited our GreenThumb colleague Babbie Dunnington, who will give us some useful advice on what plants are best to plant in the garden, especially in the non-edible raised beds, where the garden cannot plant food.  Seven-foot sunflowers were suggested at our meeting, and that is a great idea, but there are more ideas for you to see, and those of us who can join the next meeting on the computer will have a chance to look at more options together!  Babbie can also help the garden get the plants, including plants we can give you from GreenThumb and also grant options. In advance of the meeting, we will send around a list of possibilities, with pictures.


Garden hazard: Ms Hutchinson mentioned that there is a wooden plank in the garden that is a safety hazard, that was left after the garden renovation was done.  Our Parks operations teams are not visiting non-active gardens at the moment, but we will look into it before the garden opens again.


I think that is about it for the meeting, though anyone else please chime in if I missed anything.  Save space in your calendars for 4/20 at 11 am--I will get a Zoom link and send a calendar invitation out to you in the next few days.  I look forward to having you there.


Best,


Amber Qureshi, GreenThumb
